ss=headings><font color=#FFFFFF>Author</font></td><td valign=top bgcolor=203450 class=headings><font color=#FFFFFF>Comment</font></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=samspade>samspade</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(6/22/02 10:43:02 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm26.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=673.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: First SERIOUS story</span><hr size=1> Hi there, <br>
<br>
I shouldn't worry too much about posting stuff, you usually get good responses from here. <br>
<br>
You start out great, it's an evocative piece of writing.  Here are a few tips: <br>
<br>
Don't overuse overlong words such as &quot;obtrusively&quot; it's not really needed - simple and basic language is the most effective. <br>
<br>
As above, the second sentence is overlong and gets bogged down in grammar. <br>
<br>
You cut between past and present in the same sentence too many times, save the past for one sentence and sum it up in a short phrase. <br>
<br>
&quot;Standing like a scream prolonged for an eternity.&quot;  this sentence lacks a subject, which is important for all sentences. <br>
<br>
There is a repetition of birds in the last sentence.<br>
<br>
I think you should focus your attention to one solitary house, rather than generalise. <br>
<br>
I've rewritten your piece here for you to look at the changes I've made. Much of it is your own writing just reorderd, or cut out, with the focus changed. <br>
<br>
&quot;Peeked and bleak shadows danced obtrusively against the solitary house in Salem, Massachusetts. Rushed beams of moonlight tainted by claw-like branches found there way to the twisted and ugly gray slats of wood. The once crimson coloured house had warped into a scream.  A shuffling black mass of birds sat upon the peaked roof depositing their putrid waste and providing food to all the grotesque life supported within its rotting planks...&quot;<br>
<br>
My last piece of advice is to never rest on your laurels and always try to find a better way to write things, I've checked this message five times already. <br>
<br>
Oh, read a book on punctuation and grammar something that any writer, from age 12-80, should do. <br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
